ANALYSIS OF FACTORS IMPACTING THE SLEEP PROBLEM USING LOGISTIC REGRESSION

1. INTRODUCTION

This markdown file uses the sleep dataset ‘sleep.csv’.

1.1 Research Question

This analysis is concerned to identify which all factors predict the likelihood that a person is facing problem in getting sleep or not? For this analysis the predictors used are - age group,weight of a person,feeling restless and quality of sleep of a person.

1.2 Proposed Hyothesis

1.Building a proposed model to test the hypothesis that whether problem getting in sleep can be predicted by age group, weight, restless and quality of sleep factors.

2.Building a proposed model to test the hypothesis that whether problem getting in sleep can be predicted by age group, weight, restless factors.

3.Building a proposed model to test the hypothesis that whether problem getting in sleep can be predicted by age group, weight, restless and quality of sleep factors. #1.3 Read in the data

1.4 Data Description

The sleep dataset used for the statistical analysis is a real data available from Staff from a university in Melbourne, Australia which is a survey related to various aspects of people’s lives. The sleep dataset contains 268 rows and 55 columns i.e., variables. ‘Problem getting to sleep’ is considered as dependent variable and 4 predictor variables.

Inspection of normal scores for skewness and kurtosis indicated that while skewness was not an issue falling with an acceptable range of +/-2, (skewness of 1.0087407 SE=0.1552301), kurtosis was outside acceptable bounds, (kurtosis of 3.4717674 SE=0.3104602 .

Further inspection of the variable using standardized scores showed that 0.37% standardised scores were outside the acceptable range of +/3.29. Weight will therefore be treated as a normal within this analysis (m=NA, sd=NA, n=20).

In statistics outlier is an observation that is very different from the other data points. The outliers have a significant effect on the mean and standard deviation. Box plot is useful to detect the outliers in the variable. For the weight variable the outliers were present which were removed to get the statistically precise output.

4 DATA PREPARATION

Data preparation is the process of cleaning data before performing statistical analysis.It is used to find the awkward data such as missing values or outliers and to remove them.

4.1 HANDLING MISSING VALUES

When no data value is recorded for any variable then that is called as missing values. These missing values are denoted by ‘NA’. The function is.na() function in R is used to find the missing values in R for each variable. Here in the outcome variable ‘problem in getting sleep’ 2 NA values are present. Likewise in all the predictor variables few NA values are present which are removed. In this case firstly only those variables required for statistical analysis were fetched and stored in a new data frame then for continuous predictor variable ‘Weight’ the missing values are imputed by the average value and then lastly all the NA values for categorical variables are removed using na.omit() R function. As the missing values can reduce the calculated statistics precision and make the result misleading. So missing value transformations are performed.

sum(is.na(sleepdata$getsleprec))
## [1] 2
sum(is.na(sleepdata$weight))
## [1] 22
#Imputing the missing values in weight column by the average value
avgweight<- mean(sleepdata$weight,na.rm = TRUE)
avgweight<- round(avgweight)
avgweight
## [1] 73
sleepdata$weight[is.na(sleepdata$weight)]<-avgweight
View(sleepdata$weight)

sum(is.na(sleepdata$agegp3))
## [1] 23
sum(is.na(sleepdata$restlss))
## [1] 6
View(sleepdata)
#Removing few variables

sleepdf<- sleepdata[,c(6,37,49,50,53)]
View(sleepdf)
#Now removing all NA from dataset
sleepdf<-na.omit(sleepdf)
View(sleepdf)

4.3 Multicollinearity

Multicollinearity is a phenomena in which one predictor variable in a regression model is correlated to the other predictor variable with a substantial degree of accuracy. In this the correlation is checked between the predictor variables and the outcome variable by creating a correlation matrix method (Lines 263-265). As with the given variables all correlation values are found less than 0.8 so this means that no multicollinearity is found.

5.Logistic Regression

The Logistic Regression is a statistical model used to predict a categorical variable as an outcome variable from one or more categorical or continuous predictor variables. In this prediction model binary logistic regression is used where the dependent variable is coded as 0 = No and 1 = Yes. The logistic regression equation from which the probability of outcome variable Y is predicted is given by: P(Y) = 1/(1+e^-(b0+b1X1))

Where P(Y) is the probability of occurring Y, e is the base of natural logarithms, b0 is the constant,X1 is the predictor and b1 is the coefficient of X1.When there are several predictors the equation becomes: P(Y) = 1/(1+e^-(b0+b1X1+b2X2+….+bnXn))

The summary(logmodel1) function is used to get the summary of the complete model with Deviance residuals and coefficients details. Deviance Residuals, are a measure of model fit which is used as a part of the calculation of Chi-square. The residual deviance is calculated as 305.20 on 232 degrees of freedom whereas the Null deviance is calculated as 313.72 on 234 degrees of freedom. At this stage of analysis the value of deviance should be less than the value for the Null model because lower the value the model is said to be more accurate to predict the outcome variable (Field Miles). Due to some intervention the value is reduced. A Chi-square significance plus test is performed to predict how better the model can predict the outcome variable. Here the value is significant at a 0.05 level and so we can say that overall the model is predicting whether a person is getting problem to sleep or not significantly better. Degree of freedom is calculated as 2 in the model which shows the number of variables in the model. Also here the Chi- square probability is calculated which is ‘chisq.prob <- 1 - pchisq(modelChi, Chidf)’ 0.014 which is less than 0.05 which is statistically significant(p<0.05) that means the model is better in predicting the outcome. Here ??2(2) = 8.52, p = 0.014. The agegp3 predictor is statistially significant in predicting the output. A confusion matrix is calculated for the baseline model which calculated the Specificity, Sensitivity and Accuracy of the model. Here in this model Total observations n= 235 out of which 128+15=143 were predicted correctly and 76+16 =92 were wrongly predicted. Specificity: 0.483871 Sensitivity: 0.627451 Total Accuracy: 0.6085106 The Sensitivity of the model tells the percentage of people saying ‘yes’. In this case the model was able to identify 62.7% of the people who said they have problem in getting sleep. The Specificity of the model tells the percentage of people saying ‘no’. In this case the model was able to identify 48.4% of the people who said they do not have problem in getting sleep. PV+ is 30.9% which is calculated by dividing the number of predicted cases as Yes/the total number predicted. PV- is 42.9% which is calculated by dividing the number of predicted cases as no/the total number predicted. AUC the Area Under Curve is literally just the percentage of this graph that is under the curve. Here the AUC is 0.612 which is in between 0.5 and 0.8(Andy Field) Tests to see if the data met the assumption of collinearity indicated that multicollinearity was not a concern (AgeGroup, VIF= 1.01; Weight, VIF= 1.01) and were within acceptable levels (VIF <2.5) (Tarling (2008)).The tolerance of the model predictor that is the reciprocal of VIF was calculated which was not a concern (AgeGroup, 1/VIF= 0.99; Weight, 1/VIF= 0.99) and were within acceptable range(Tolerance >0.4) (Tarling (2008)).

7.Result and Discussion

In this analysis the outcome variable is person’s problem getting to sleep is analysed using predictor variables Age group,weight,Feeling Restlessand quality of sleep using logistic regression. Total three models are analysed by adding a new predictor each time.This is the Forward Logistic regression model.First model is tested for two predictors age group and weight.Then the next model is created by adding a new predictor restless and finally another predictor Quality of sleep variable is added.The p-value for predictor is calculated within the model to check the statistical significance of predictors.The overall accuracy of model 1 was 60.8%,model 2 was 63.4% and lastly model 3 was 68.9%.

The most significant predictors were age group and qualityof sleep.In model 2 by adding a new predictor the (Log Likelihood = -156.86) and in model 3 (Log Likelihood = -137.75) staistically proves that the model 3 is the best fit model. As lesser the Log Likelihood value better is the accuracy of the model(Andy Field).The Confusion matrix count,accuracy,sensiiity,ROC curve all statistical factors proves that model 3 is the best fit.
